sponseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior two-thirds receives blood from one midline vessel","First cervical foramen marks the vertebral artery entry point","Basilar artery gives rise to dorsal supply vessels","Carotid system gives origin to vertebral vessels","Ventral vessel supplies dorsal spinal cord region"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior two-thirds receives blood from one midline vessel\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. This artery runs along the anterior median fissure of the spinal cord and is formed by the union of branches from the vertebral arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst cervical foramen marks the vertebral artery entry point\u003C/strong\u003E - They enter at C6 and ascend through the transverse foramina to C1\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasilar artery gives rise to dorsal supply vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - They arise from the vertebral arteries before they join to form the basilar artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid system gives origin to vertebral vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - They arise from the subclavian arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentral vessel supplies dorsal spinal cord region\u003C/strong\u003E - The posterior third is supplied by the posterior spinal arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe anterior spinal artery and paired posterior spinal arteries form a continuous arterial supply along the length of the spinal cord, with segmental reinforcement from radicular arteries at various levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The subclavian arteries give rise to the vertebral arteries which pass through the transverse foramina from C6 to 